Conclusions and prospects
In summary, the simplicity and high efficiency of the CRISPR/Cas9 system allows affordable
e
lgenome editing. In addition, the large sgRNA library will make both drug target identification
and function screening more efficient. This RNA-guided genome editing tool also gives rise
c
ito the potential to change the genetic landscape of animals and plants around us to obtain the
tdesired genotypes at will.
rThe application of this system has been expanded beyond genome editing, to areas such as
gene expression regulation or specific chromatin labeling using fluorescent protein. Although
Agreat achievements have been made to improve the specificity and expand the application of
this technology, there is still have plenty of room for improvement and extension.
The specificity of this system still needs improvement. A major concern for application of
d
this system is off-target mutagenesis. In the past two years, many papers have reported
eoff-target events of this system. Many efforts such as paired nickases, tru-gRNAs, and
tdimeric FokI-dCas9 nucleases were exploited to reduce off-target effects. Although these
modifications have reduced the off-target events significantly, further improvement will be
pneeded especially for the more precise modifications or therapeutic applications. Further
optimization of this system needs unbiased strategies for more comprehensive evaluation of
e
the off-target effects. Meanwhile, the mechanisms underlying target search remains unclear.
c
Learning more about the mechanisms of the target search and cleavage will provide the basis
cfor improvement of Cas9 and/or sgRNA to increase the specificity.
Another area for improvement is to shift the balance of HDR:NHEJ from NHEJ-mediated
